That&#x27;s a delegation strategy, which is a very limited form of composition.<p>A class with a trait/role can be queried for that interface:<p><pre><code>  smile() if $my_object->does(&#x27;SomeTrait&#x27;);

</code></pre>
Methods provided by a trait/role have direct access to $self.<p>Also, Moose gives you the ability to apply traits to classes that are not predefined with those traits:<p><pre><code>  use Moose::Util;
  my $instance = Moose::Util::with_traits(&#x27;MooseClass&#x27;, &#x27;MyTrait&#x27;)->new(%params);

</code></pre>
You can parameterize roles (as in, pass parameters that affect what the role provides).  If you put some method modifiers into your roles, you can enhance existing functionality; for example, you can add logging, memoization, and persistence, all without the class having those features beforehand.<p>In other words, roles/traits make your OOP functionality much more composable.

alu.vhd, lines 40 - 42<p><pre><code>      -- arithmetic
       alu_results.add_result <= std_logic_vector( signed( nos ) + signed( tos ) );
       alu_results.sub_result <= std_logic_vector( signed( nos ) - signed( tos ) );
</code></pre>
This logic can be done with one adder instead of two.  In two&#x27;s complement, invert the 2nd operand and assert the carry in.
